arch:property.oc:show_val: South part of the westernmost wall of the temple precinct

Phase IV: Nabataean Grand Design: 1st c. BCE to CE 1st c. The remainder of the subterranean canalization is installed including the East Plaza Great Cistern. The East and South Perimeter Walls are installed and Rooms A and B and the Tabun Cave Room are built into the casemate of the East Perimeter Wall. The East Plaza and South Passageway are paved and the temple Forecourt is raised and laid with a small hexagonal pavement. Residential Quarter is built in the southwest corner of the precinct. Also at this time the Central Staircase of Phase II is blocked and the lateral East and West Staircases are constructed to access the Lower Temenos.
3.00 m north south (exposed)-by-0.85 m east west.

Locus 21 is the lower courses of the south edge of the temple West Perimeter Wall, which serves as the westernmost wall of the precinct proper. The wall is constructed from medium to large hewn sandstone ashlars which are wet-laid with mortar. Overall, the exposed remains of the wall are in stable condition. In construction the wall measures two rows thick and two courses are visible in the west. The base of the wall was not reached. Locus 21 has been assigned to this stage because it bonds to the South Perimeter Wall (Locus 7), making the two features contemporary constructions.
Bonded to the west edge of the temple South Perimeter Wall.
Construction and early use of architectural features belonging to the temple's tetrastyle in antis expansion.
